ellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/E006124/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>The research aims to explore the working of faith-based organisations and their engagement with development processes. The primary objective is to produce a book monograph on the working of Pakistani madrasas? the oldest institution of learning in the Muslim world which has currently become suspect of promoting international terrorism? and their relationship with the development processes in the country. &lt;/p> 
&lt;p>The research develops a typology of Pakistani madrasas, investigates the factors that make parents and students choose madrasa education over secular schools, analyses the basis of community support for madrasas, and documents the factors leading to rise of female madrasas. The underlying theoretical concern it to explore how religion, defined as an institutional arrangement and modes of living to which sacred status has been given by a set of beliefs and values, impacts individual behaviour and development processes, and how these beliefs and values and their organisational manifestations in turn are influenced by the socio-economic and political developments within a given society.&lt;/p> 
&lt;p>The research draws upon the ethnographic study of a Deobandi madrasa conducted for the DPhil thesis plus an additional six month fieldwork carried out with students, parents, teachers, and donors of a large sample of madrasas of different scale, sect and educational level, including female madrasas, during 2006. In addition, the student enrolment data available with the five central madrasa regulatory boards in Pakistan has been analysed. &lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2009-01-31</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2007-02-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>132741</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs><gtr:impactSummaryOutput><gtr:description>Yes, I have provided details of it in the ESRC end of the award impact report.</gtr:description><gtr:firstYearOfImpact>2009</gtr:firstYearOfImpact><gtr:id>A29F8249-0499-40D1-8CC4-DBDCEDC6CA47</gtr:id><gtr:impactTypes><gtr:impactType>Societal,Economic</gtr:impactType></gtr:impactTypes><gtr:outcomeId>544e90c9cbb6e2.96785277</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:sector>Education</gtr:sector></gtr:impactSummaryOutput></gtr:impactSummaryOutputs><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:description>These are listed in my end of the award report submited to ESRC.</gtr:description><gtr:exploitationPathways>I have helped DFID education sector support programme in Nigeria an integrated education model for Quranic and Islamic schools. The lessons can be learnt by other Muslim countries dealing with a large number of out of schools children.</gtr:exploitationPathways><gtr:id>29CC6EBA-CE74-428B-AA52-B728B1149E2D</gtr:id><gtr:outcomeId>544e91761d35a6.3281